<p>a domain you registered for a side project expires. you don't notice. within 24 hours, it's registered by a squatter who wants £2,000 for it — ten times what you paid. your project email stops working. your portfolio site goes dark. getting it back costs more than the domain is worth, but rebuilding without it costs even more.</p>

<p>this scenario plays out thousands of times a year. domain renewal is one of the most preventable financial losses, yet it keeps happening because the renewal email lands in a promotions folder or the contact address is an old one you no longer check.</p>

<h4>why domains are different</h4>

<p>most auto-renewals cost you money slowly — a few extra pounds each month. domains can cost you everything at once. lose a domain and you lose not just the name but everything tied to it: email addresses, website, ssl certificates, dns records. recovery is possible but expensive, and some registrars auction expired domains immediately, making repossession difficult.</p>

<h4>the notice problem</h4>

<p>icann requires registrars to send renewal reminders 30, 7, and 1 day before expiry. in practice, these emails are easy to miss. they look like marketing. they come from addresses you don't recognise. and if you registered the domain through a reseller, the reminder chain might break entirely.</p>

